03750nmm a2200625Ia 9781501711381DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20182004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017113817 a10.7591/97815017113812doi  a(DE-B1597)515516  a(OCoLC)1083621651  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR457b.Y68 2004eb04a820.9/1452221 aYousef, Nancy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIsolated Cases :bThe Anxieties of Autonomy in Enlightenment Philosophy and Romantic Literature /cNancy Yousef. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (272 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe literature of the romantic period has consistently been seen as the source of modern concepts of the individual. Nancy Yousef maintains, however, that the dominant account of the self in romanticism is in need of profound revision. While individuals presented in central texts of the period are indeed often alone or separated from others, Yousef regards this isolation as a problem the texts attempt to illuminate, rather than a condition they construct as normative or desirable. As her argument moves from the eighteenth to the nineteenth century, through both philosophical and literary writing, her book offers a new account of autonomy and of the complex romantic inheritance of enlightenment preoccupations with the origins of human association and the course of human development.In her richly interdisciplinary book, Nancy Yousef addresses the emergence of autonomy, demonstrating that the ideal was beset from its beginnings by profound concerns over the possibilities and grounds of human relations and interdependence. Isolated Cases draws attention to the strain of intersubjective anxieties and longings hidden within representations of the individual as self-sufficient and self-defining. Among the writers and thinkers Yousef treats at length are John Locke, John Stuart Mill, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Mary Shelley, and William Wordsworth.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aAnxiety in literature. 0aAutonomy (Philosophy). 0aAutonomy (Psychology) in literature. 0aEnglish literaturexFrench influences. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnlightenment. 0aPhilosophy in literature. 0aRomanticismzGreat Britain. 4aEngland. 4aLiterary Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150171138140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501711381423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501711381/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles